The fortress of Duu-da-bheann was on the north- western edge of the true Ultonian territory, while Duo-Ceithern was within the debateable ground which now constitutes the north of the county of Londonderry. Cethern was of the stock of Ir‚ from which the Irish Picts are said to have derived their origin (Ogyg. p. 190; Reeves' Ec, Ant. p. 336); but the possession passed from his family to the sons of Niali, and remained so until the battle of Ocha, when it was temporarily restored to the Dalaradians or Picts. (See note ⁰, p. 32, supra.) lt was recovered by the Hy Neill after the battle of Moin-doire-lothair in 563 (ibim), and thence- forward was a scene of contentiori between the rival races.
